properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Continuing widespread power outages expected this morning. Many communities received 10 to 25 mm of ice accretion from an impactful winter storm since midday on Saturday. Although the freezing rain has now ended, strong wind gusts near 40 km/h are expected to continue this morning before easing off early this afternoon. Ice accretion on trees or power lines, in addition to the strong wind gusts this morning, has the potential to cause widespread power outages. Additionally pedestrians and drivers should exercise caution as falling tree branches could cause sidewalks or roads to become hazardous. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

properties.Title: Snowfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: 5 to 20 cm of snow by this afternoon. The low pressure system continues its trek across the south coast this morning. In the wake of the low this afternoon, northeast outflow winds will collide with northwest winds from the Strait of Georgia. Where they meet, a localised band of heavy snow will develop and push through Metro Vancouver this evening for further localised accumulations of 5 cm. Higher elevations of West Vancouver, North Vancouver and Coquitlam will continue to see snow today with a further 5 to 10 cm. Vancouver, Burnaby and New Westminster will see wet snow mixed with rain. Precipitation type will depend on proximity to the water, elevation, precipitation intensity and wind direction. A further 5 cm is forecast for these cities. Inland sections of Metro Vancouver - SE such as north Surrey and Langley will continue to see snow today with local accumulations of 2 to 4 cm. Southern sections will see rain, at times mixed with snow, as southerly winds keep temperatures above zero. Richmond, Delta, Tsawwassen and Ladner will continue to see rain today as the southerly winds have been keeping temperatures above freezing. ### Rapidly accumulating snow could make travel difficult over some locations. Surfaces such as highways, roads, walkways and parking lots may become difficult to navigate due to accumulating snow. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm.

properties.Title: Arctic Outflow Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Very strong outflow winds and severely cold wind chill values are expected or occurring. A prolonged period of frigid temperatures, very strong arctic outflow winds and wind chill values of minus 20 and below continue. The arctic ridge of high pressure over the BC interior responsible for these conditions will persist through the week. ### Frostbite and hypothermia can occur within minutes if adequate precautions are not taken when outdoors. Arctic outflow warnings are issued when bitterly cold air flows from the interior to coastal communities and the outflow winds create wind chill values of -20 or less for 6 hours or more. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm.
